<paragraph id="8BB8D54179369F624ACAFC46FC1019D1" blockId="17.[151,1437,663,1480]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<bibRefCitation id="EF96A8B079369F624ACAFC46FE2D1FD9" author="De Marmels, J." box="[199,437,916,941]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="249 - 262" refId="ref50706" refString="De Marmels, J. (2012) Review of the &quot; metallic group &quot; of species of Argia Rambur known from Venezuela, with description of the larva of Argia jocosa Hagen in Selys, 1865 (Odonata: Coenagrionidae). International Journal of Odonatology, 15 (3), 249 - 262. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 13887890.2012.717906" type="journal article" year="2012">De Marmels (2012)</bibRefCitation>
provided a thorough review of this species within 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624E36FC47FB361FD8" box="[1083,1198,916,941]" name="Venezuela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
and cleared up its misidentification with 
<taxonomicName id="4C07AEC279369F624B9AFC6BFDB31FA5" box="[407,555,952,976]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cupraurea">
<emphasis id="B973095379369F624B9AFC6BFDB31FA5" box="[407,555,952,976]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A. cupraurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Its male is the most variable of all of the metallic red species. The 
<typeStatus id="54BC6BE379369F624F38FC64FA041FA5" box="[1333,1436,951,976]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">lectotype</typeStatus>
(Fig. 50) is characterized, as 
<bibRefCitation id="EF96A8B079369F624BD7FC0FFDE61F81" author="Calvert, P. P." box="[474,638,988,1013]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="17 - 72" refId="ref50307" refString="Calvert, P. P. (1901) Odonata. In: Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O. (Eds.), Biologia Centrali Americana-Insecta Neuroptera. R. H. Porter &amp; Dulau Co., London, pp. 17 - 72." type="book chapter" year="1901">Calvert (1901)</bibRefCitation>
noted by &quot;Segments 3–7 black on dorsum, basal half of 3–6 blue, 8–10 blue on dorsum.&quot; Most males of this species (including all those known from 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F6249FBFC2CFBF3186D" box="[1014,1131,1023,1048]" name="Venezuela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
) differ in having S3–5 blue for two-thirds or more of their length (as in Fig. 52). The male from Bellavista River, 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624E75FBF7FB4D1848" box="[1144,1237,1060,1085]" name="Ecuador" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(Fig. 52) has the inferior black on S3–6 thicker than on males from 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F6248D1FB94FCD21815" box="[732,842,1095,1120]" name="Colombia" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624989FB94FC631815" box="[900,1019,1095,1120]" name="Venezuela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
. Another male from Lloraudo River, 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624A9AFBBFFE9D18F0" box="[151,261,1132,1157]" name="Colombia" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Colombia</collectingCountry>
has S3–7 predominantly black (Fig. 51) thus approaching the color pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="4C07AEC279369F624E93FBBEFB7218F1" authorityName=": Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" box="[1182,1258,1133,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuprea">
<emphasis id="B973095379369F624E93FBBEFB7218F1" box="[1182,1258,1133,1156]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">cuprea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like species 
<taxonomicName id="4C07AEC279369F624F89FBBFFF4918DD" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dives">
<emphasis id="B973095379369F624F89FBBFFF4918DD" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A. dives</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C07AEC279369F624B05FB43FEE818DD" authorityName="Garrison &amp; von Ellenrieder" authorityYear="2018" box="[264,368,1168,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philipi">
<emphasis id="B973095379369F624B05FB43FEE818DD" box="[264,368,1168,1192]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A. philipi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The thoracic dorsum is normally entirely metallic (as in 
<figureCitation id="133CC9C479369F6249F7FB5CFBD318DD" box="[1018,1099,1167,1192]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–22" captionStartId="42.[151,264,1830,1852]" captionTargetBox="[172,1401,213,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@42.[150,1436,193,1809]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 19–22. Color pattern of male head, thorax, and S1–4. Head, dorsal view, thorax and S1–4, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770047/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) but the male from Bellavista River, 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624AE8FB67FEDA18B8" box="[229,322,1204,1229]" name="Ecuador" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="133CC9C479369F624B58FB67FE3218B9" box="[341,426,1204,1229]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–18" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1893,1915]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,200,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[150,1436,193,1872]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 14–18. Color pattern of male head, thorax, and S1–4. Head, dorsal view, thorax and S1–4, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770045/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) has a narrow blue antehumeral stripe and another male from Reserva Natural El Rey Zamuro, 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624AF2FB04FEF51885" box="[255,365,1239,1264]" name="Colombia" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Colombia</collectingCountry>
has a similar pale antehumeral stripe that is about as wide as the middorsal black stripe. The middorsal and humeral stripe, the latter of which is divided above at its upper third, show no metallic coloration although metallic reflections are present on the prothorax and head. All of these males conform to what we believe to represent 
<taxonomicName id="4C07AEC279369F624B27FA97FE0F1929" authorityName="Hagen in Selys" authorityYear="1865" box="[298,407,1348,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jocosa">
<emphasis id="B973095379369F624B27FA97FE0F1929" box="[298,407,1348,1372]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A. jocosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the male appendages and genital ligula (unique for this species) match those of the 
<typeStatus id="54BC6BE379369F624A9AFAB4FF6619F5" box="[151,254,1383,1408]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">lectotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="133CC9C479369F624B00FAB4FEF919F5" box="[269,353,1383,1408]" captionStart="FIGURES 94–97" captionStartId="53.[151,264,1884,1906]" captionTargetBox="[166,1425,211,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[151,1436,193,1862]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURES 94–97. Genital ligula. (a) lateral view; (b) ectal view; (c) entolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770064" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770064/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 95</figureCitation>
). The Bellavista River pair represents a new record for 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F6249C0FAB4FBB519F5" box="[973,1069,1383,1408]" name="Ecuador" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. We also examined an additional 
<specimenCount id="9D011EC879369F624A9AFA5FFF6A19D1" box="[151,242,1420,1445]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="male">296 ♂♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="9D011EC879369F624B25FA5FFEF619D0" box="[296,366,1420,1445]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="female">75♀♀</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F624BBEFA5FFDB919D0" box="[435,545,1420,1445]" name="Colombia" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F31095D179369F62485AFA5FFD5219D0" box="[599,714,1420,1445]" name="Venezuela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
for this account.
</paragraph>
